author: azerie

title: Smart Dump Bucket With Nozzle Cleaner

description.text: This is a catch bucket where the 3D printer may purge any old plastic and then clean itself.  Of note is also the optical interrupt that is attached to the bucket.  The intention is that this would allow the machine to be better able to detect nozzle jams and keep the enclosure clean.

Current designs probably require this to be mounted on the end of the makerbot build table. (Ideally you would do this with bucket hanging off the back of the table so you don't loose to much build envelop, but I don't know if you could pull this off without causing collisions.
Do note, the attached models are for a custom 3D printer that differs from the Cupcake frame, but conceptually provides some useful ideas for keeping any 3D printer running well.

title: Portafilter Holder for La Pavoni Pub and Bar models

description.text:
This is a portafilter holder for the bigger models La Pavoni Pub and Bar type portafilters.
The holder is tested and stable and can be mounted to the side of the La Pavoni machines using strong double sided tape.

Printer:

XYZPrinting Da Vinci Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

40%

Notes:

I use BuildTak on my printed bed and don't need a raft. If you print on Kapton Tape or Painters Tape, you will need a raft of 10mm

Mine is printed with ABS on 210C nozzle and 90C bed.
Sand if needed.

I saw another model that didn't work out for me because it was to small so I made a new one that was big enough for my portaholders.

Original idea was from Sigshoj, but my model is not a remake but a brand new design. If you have a smaller model La Pavoni Machine, You can find his model here:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1500910

Always be careful when printing objects you wish to use for food or drinks. Directly eating or drinking out of a printed object might be dangerous because of plastic weakeners and other pollution in the print material.

Don't let food come in direct contact with your prints unless you know for sure you use a safe type of filament.

description.text: This little adapter allows standard Lego beams to attach to standard servo motors

comments.text: I feel like trying to print splines would be too troublesome and tricky for a lot of printers. My advice would be to simply put a drop of threadlocker or superglue in the mounting hole, then put the servo in (this is, of course, assuming you already know the proper orientation for the adapter).

author: arnevdm

title: Bender Head Soda Can Holder (with straw hole)

description.text:
Inspired by prints from Joel - The "3D Printing Nerd"

It looked so barbaric to see someone drink from his head without the top.

This can also be used to hide what you're drinking.

Choose either with hole in bottom or without. The hole in the bottom is to allow sweat to drip out, prevent suction, and allow you to push the can out.

Choose bottom closed to prevent any leaks. This version can be used as a drinking cup, if you feel safe enough to drink from your print and possibly get the top and bottom pieces to seal shut.

Blender 2.76a, Bender Bust by cerberus333, LoboCNC Can Thermos (No Longer Available)

I don't like to use the Boolean function too often when modeling when I know it is for 3D printing.
So, I needed to remove the outer shells of the Soda Can Thermos by LoboCNC.
I scaled and separated Bender's head into two sections by duplicating it and remove the opposite pieces from each file.
Finally, I needed to painstakingly combine each matching edge with new faces and add a hole through the antenna to receive a straw. (6.5mm diameter straws from Sonic Drive-In)

After my first print, I enlarged the diameter of the antenna to receive a larger straw. The threading was too close to the outer edge of the top half. So I adjusted it to prevent thin walls and possible holes. There were also faces behind the eyes of the original file I removed for easier printing.

I would recommend a "Bendy" straw. (If too long, cut straw to just above the top of the antenna)

print_settings.Notes:: This was a challenge to print in ABS on a DaVinci 1.0 and keep from warping. I've since switched to a Rostock Max V2 with a PEI bed, so bed adhesion issues are now a forgotten thing of the past for me.

description.text:
I used this in constructing a present for a friend in combination with the Skull With Pointed Teeth, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:31998.

By modifying the OpenSCAD source, I removed the lamp holder, hollowed out most of the main base, and relocated the cord hole slightly. This gave me more room for electronics and wiring for LED's inserted directly into the skull. I placed red 3mm LEDs inside a 10% fill directly behind the eyes which worked really, really well. I also scattered some slow color changing LED's throughout the rest of the skull; I placed switches for both of those effects in the hollow base.

Unfortunately, I stupidly forgot to take some pics before delivery.

I made the enlarged hollow roomy enough for an Arduino Micro, Nano, or Teensy, so I'm planning to go with Neopixels for general lighting on my next build, with 5mm RGB LEDs connected to PWM pins for illuminating the eyes.

Printer:

XYZ DaVinci 1.0

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.200 layer height

Infill:

20%

Notes:

This was a challenge to print in ABS on a DaVinci 1.0 and keep from warping. I've since switched to a Rostock Max V2 with a PEI bed, so bed adhesion issues are now a forgotten thing of the past for me.

Schrader valve cap with customizable top text for recommended air pressure.

I was inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:780404 for this cap but this is a completely independent design.

The internal thread is created with the threads.scad library by D. Kirshner, see
http://dkprojects.net/openscad-threads/.

This design is meant to show the potential of 3-d printing. I do not advise to use this cap on any critical valve, like on e.g. car or bike tires etc.
If you use this cap on a valve, you do so at your own risk. Make sure that the cap does not depress the valve pin, and that it does not deflate the tire, air shock, or whatsoever.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Simple Black

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Can be printed up-side down or up-side up.
Rotate along z-axis such that the clearance layer of the square clearance in the top of the cap is parallel to the tool path in this layer.




To print the text in a different color, I printed the cap up-side down. I used 10 skirt lines.
Before printing I inserted the filament with the text color into the extruder, and extruded until this color appeared cleanly at the nozzle. Next, I changed the filament by pulling the old filament and pushing the new filament in until it stops without extruding. Then I started printing.

Early concept for a fully symmetric belt-driven extruder carriage for upgrading Prusa Mendel. Belt-driven means there's no stepper motor on the X-carriage, so it can be much lighter and move much faster. It has two X-belts that are controlled by one stepper on each side. If both belts move in the same direction, the X-carriage moves in that direction too. If both belts move in opposite directions, the extruder moves but the X-carriage stands still. x_motion = (stepper1 + stepper2) / 2
extruder = (stepper1 - stepper2) / 2 We'll need new firmware to control x_motion and extruder independently by setting the correct speed for each stepper motor for the two belts. stepper1 = x_motion + extruder
stepper2 = x_motion - extruder This design attempts to reduce the effects of the torque that's required to move the extruder:
  • It is based on the excellent VertX (vertical x-axis) by watsdesign with LM8UU linear bearings: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10711
  • It uses a pretty large timing belt pulley on the back of the carriage.
  • The two belts are entering the carriage very close together and perfectly parallel.
This is an early concept. Feedback is welcome!

comments.text: Great idea to remove the motor off the axis and a novel solution, but there may be a simpler way. keep the x axis as current prusa, but turn the extruder 90 degree around the z axis. Drive the extruder using a motor mounted at the end of the axis with a square or hexagon bar mounted horizontally. The extruder drive gear moves along the shaft when the x axis moves, but can still be driven by the motor at any point.

comments.text: That's a great idea too! I made a similar proof of concept to take the X motor off the carriage (which isn't actually that useful) but it uses a similar idea by using a square rod to drive and the carriage slides through it: http://garyhodgson.com/reprap/2011/09/experimental-off-carriage-x-axis/http://garyhodgson.com/reprap/...
comments.author: martinprice2004

comments.text:
I'm certainly no EE, but how hard would it be to make an interface board that would "add
&
amp; subtract" the X motor steps from the extruder steps? If that could be plugged in between the command signals to the stepper drives and the stepper drives themselves, so no software changes would be required, and this could potentially work with any machine.
comments.author: NEATman

comments.text: The actual electronics would be dead simple. The actual promblem is getting the step commands to send at a regular rate (hint: you need the firmware to do that). Let's look at X moving slowly and E moving somewhat faster, at a constant velocity. These are their "step" and "direction signals: (^ is supposed top be a high signal, or step command, _ a low signal)
comments.author: NEATman

comments.text: My concern with this would be how much will the extruder drive affect the accuracy of the X positioning. Having the extruder motor on the carriage like the traditional design means that extruding doesnt cause any (significant) forces on the carriage. In your design it will apply torque to the carriage so the rigidity of the carriage mounts and rails will be much more significant. The existing 8mm rails dont require much force to deflect by a mm or so, and that would cause signigficant quality issues with a print.
comments.author: GregFrost

comments.text: You're making a good point about torque. I have improved the design, and added torque considerations in the description.

Gusev Crater, Mars from the NASA 3D model library. Created by Ames SpaceShop

The original file had a very thin base. I've thickened it to make the model a little more durable.

Download the original file here: http://nasa3d.arc.nasa.gov/detail/SpiritLanding

After printing I glued sand to the flat areas and painted the model with acrylics and inks.

Glue the two halves together, then fill any gaps with plaster, clay or any other hard-drying household filler. Paint with acrylics and inks.

remixed_from.author: ChatterComa
remixed_from.title: Vise pad for holding 8mm threaded rod

title: Parametric Motor Shaft Bench Vise Holder

description.text: The youtube video here https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DBnKPEnt9a4 shows how to add flats to motor shafts that do not yet have them. Loosely based on the "Vise pad for holding 8mm threaded rod by ChatterComa" I created the part that helps you to grip the motor shaft properly in place so that you do not apply force to the motor inners.

• Measure your magnet if you want, edit the OpenScad-File.
  • Render, export as STL, print
  • Insert magnet if you want
  • Follow the instructions of the video
  • Certainly to not forget to seal the motor
  • Insert motor into the printed parts
  • File
  • Be happy

description.text:
The above sea level height-data for this model is taken from the Space Shuttle Radar Topography Mission dataset (http://dwtkns.com/srtm/) and the seafloor is from the NOAA's ETOPO1 dataset (http://maps.ngdc.noaa.gov/viewers/wcs-client/).

After combining the two heightmaps I displaced the terrain onto a high-resolution plane and added surrounding walls exactly in line with the sea level. Once the sea-floor was painted, I poured liquid resin onto the model up to the walls. After the resin had set I painted the islands. The model is painted with acrylics and inks.

Notes:

I printed with 3 bottom layers and 4 top layers, to ensure a smooth sea floor.

Resin fill

Using any hard-setting liquid resin, fill the model up to the sea level (the side walls are in-line with the sea level) to create a transparent ocean.

I found SAMLEGO2's Tippmann 98 Supressor (Smart Parts 14inch barrel) and really loved the idea.

I have a Tippman Gryphon FX. I did change the size slightly for my barrel but it seems I made it a tad too small and that prompted be to make this derivative and modify it to this extent.

The one thing I did not like about his design was the amount of effort required to mount and remove the suppressor for the gun's barrel so I came up with the idea of the adapter which stays on the gun and you just screw the suppressor on and off.

I opened up the front of the adapter's I.D. to 22.125mm and the rear to 22.25mm so it slides on just snug enough to not bind on the barrel.

The adapter also allows you to experiment with different suppressor sizes/designs.

PLEASE NOTE: As mentioned before the adapter is for my Gryphon FX so you might have to adjust the adapter to fit your gun's barrel.

At the time of SAMLEGO2's writing he said it should suppress the sound by about 50%. Now, I can't say percentage wise how much it does suppress the sound but it does definitely make a noticeable difference given the size.

I am already in process of designing some new suppressors experimenting with size and then with internal design.

For this one I used cotton wool for the muffling material like SAMLEGO2 suggested but I also want to experiment with steel wool to see what the difference might be.

description.text:
Update: Added V2 to hopefully fix the issue with ethernet/hdmi fit

Case for a PCDuino 3.

Note: Included is a lid with no top holes to keep it clean for anyone who wants to add holes for wires, fans, lights, switches, etc.

Chances are with no air holes the pcduino will overheat so be sure to add your own air holes before printing, whether that's just passive air holes or a spot for a cooling fan.

Top and bottom halves each have a matching version that includes (or not) the analog audio port. Make sure you pick a matching pair.

Printer:

home made, picked fresh from the garden

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25 or better

Infill:

10% or more

Notes:

Print the main body in regular material and the feet in flexible if possible.

To assemble, use screws long enough to poke out the bottom of the case and screw the feet on to provide an air gap underneath. Alternatively use shorter screws and just glue on some rubber feet.

Mounting holes in the PCB are quite close to components (not something I can control) so the use of nylon screws is strongly recommended to avoid damage / short circuits.

This interior is designed for a scx10/ trail truck. I designed everything my self. Not everything is perfect but it will look good an almost any truck. Any design questions or comments are welcome thanks! This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1ppYVBMYjMS

So this is in multiple pieces. It took me about 5 days to figure out how i wanted to lay everything out and how I wanted it to look. To print this I would use a printer like the Formlabs 2 or some other resin type printer This project is still on going and I will try to add on even more details. Happy printing and happy crawling!

It is a printable version of an automatic valve 3 servo controlled way. I took inspiration from the project " ( Customizable ) Automated Diverter Valve " by TheHeadlessSourceMan .

This is still a project in development , if someone wants to test it and if anyone has any suggestions we might work to create a working and final version.

At this time I have not managed to get a completely no water leaks version . You have to test various configurations of seals.

See the instruction

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

EVO by NicolaP.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

30/40 %

Requirements

MATERIAL NEEDED:

6 x M3*30mm screws and M3 bolts
1 x Servo SM-S4303R (probably you can change this but it may not fits in the supports)
1 x Circular servo horn (you can find it in the servo package)
5 x O-rings (D=20mm d=15mm soft rubber)
1 x O-ring (you have to test the dimensions) that you have to apply in "Deviatore 2" to avoid vertical fluid passage
1 x rubber gasket to secure the perimeter of the valve (as the black one you see in the picture)

Instruction

-The assembly order must be that of the exploded view in picture. If you want a functional model you MUST add the O-rings.

-With a screwdriver mount all screw and bolt and secure that wather cannot pass through the jont. you can find the position between the two parts with all the holes axis are coincident

-Apply some glue to the "deviatore_servo" in the upper parts and fix it to servo horn

-Mounts the servo with the two screws you have probably found in its packaging

-Control the servo with an Arduino but remember that you have to power the servo with a separate power lines (like 5v regulator beacore arduino cannot supply all the current for this application)

IMPOSTANT NOTE:
-You have to finish all the parts that don't fits in each other manually with fine sandpaper

title: Lens cap holder v2 for 52 and 58mm cap

description.text:
retrouver l'article sur : http://blog.callondann.fr/?p=10

Bonjour,

J’ai longtemps regardé sur internet les différents lenscap holder à imprimer en 3D et je n’en avais pas trouvé qui répondait à mes besoins, j’ai donc décidé d’en créer un.

Je vous présente donc mon lenscap holder pour 2 types de capuchons d’objectif: les 58mm et les 52mm.

Il est adapté à la sangle d’appareil photo canon et est imprimable en 3D.

Vous pouvez voir les dimensions sur le dessins technique ci-dessous. (4mm d’épaisseur)

http://blog.callondann.fr/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Lenscap-holder-v2-1024x724.jpg

Une fois la conception finie sur le logiciel Autodesk Inventor, j’ai voulu l’imprimer en 3D dans mon fablab. Cet endroit met à disposition des imprimantes 3D.

Le premier prototype avait montré ses faiblesses notamment au niveau des anses où passe la sangle. Donc j’ai créé un deuxième prototype qui est parfaitement fonctionnel et résistant.

Les photos ci-dessous montrent ainsi le lenscap holder et son adaptation avec un bouchon de 58mm clipsé dessus. On peut également y mettre un bouchon de 52mm au centre dans le plus petit alésage.

Pour l’impression j’ai utilisé une Ultimaker 2 pour faire les deux lens cap holder en 1 heure ce qui revient donc à 2,50€ par unité ce qui est tout a fait acceptable.

J’ai utilisé les paramètres suivant pour l’impression dans le logiciel cura :
http://blog.callondann.fr/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/parametres.png
http://blog.callondann.fr/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/parametre-2.png

Les fichiers d’impressions sont au format STL et je les mets à disposition pour une utilisation personnelle ou familiale, j’exclue donc toute utilisation commerciale de votre part.

N’hésitez pas à laisser un commentaire sur cet article pour toutes questions relative au lenscap holder, ou à me contacter.

description.text:
This spool holder is designed for the Hesine Anet A8 Printer. Maybe works with similar printers too. It uses the included M8-threaded rod which is delivered within the kit for the original spool holder.
It can handle at least 1 kg rolls.
The system simply slides over the backplate of the LCD Screen.
Changing the spool is easy: Remove one of the M8-nuts on one side and disassemble the rod. Then you can slide out the spool easily.

If some printed strings are not attached well, local buckling appears do not worry.
Do not use without M8 rod. The long tube beam section is not supposed to work without rod enforcement.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

30

Notes:

Outer Shell thickness about 0.8mm.
Designed in Catia V5

title: F1 Ferrari Steering Wheel 2016 Version (OSW and Thrustmaster base compatible)

description.text:
STILL WORK IN PROGRESS

New version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:717948

I´ve changed the old G25 and now the wheel is Open Sim Wheel compatible.
25/02/2017 Added new body,quick release and paddlebase to make the wheel compatible with the Thrustmaster base.
NOT PRINTED OR TESTED YET,the files are thrustf1base,thrustf1paddlebase and thrustf1quick

The thickness of the base is increased due to the OSW higher torque (2.5 mm on the 2015 version vs 5 mm on this).I have the wheel tested and feels quite rigid right now.

The quick release is a remix from one made by RacingMat.
You need one of this https://www.decathlon.es/abrazadera-sillin-349-mm-id_3640502.html to attach to the OSW motor shaft.
The part gamuza2016.stl is made with filaflex.You need 4 (2 of them mirrowed) and glue them to the wheel.I´ve used Loctite.

For the shifter paddles print 2 manetacambio_b.stl or 2 manetacambio_corta.stl (this is 15mm shorter if feels better to you).One of them needs to be mirrowed.
Print also 2 manetacambio_a.stl,one of them mirrowed too,and 1 basecambio.stl.
The quick release is ready to install 2 more paddles for the clutch in the lower position.I do not use them,but if you want go ahead.The parts are the same as above.

The printer settings are almost the same that with the old wheel.
The body,cover,and paddles are printed with e3d volcano 1mm nozzle with 0.5 layer height and 2 perimeters.
For the piña23mm.stl use 100% infill and 0.2 layer height with 2 perimeters.
For the gamuza2016.stl,0.1mm layer height and 2 perimeters.
Perhaps you must increase the perimeters if you have a narrow nozzle.
31/07/2016 Added STEPS.7z Files on .stp format on request
11/07/2017 Added pegatas.7z buttons stickers on request

LIST OF MATERIALS Cooming soon
The buttons and encoders are almost the same on the 2015 version.
The buttons showed in the pictures are http://www.leobodnar.com/shop/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=98_74&products_id=190,but this ones are a little hard to push,you can use the old ones if you like.

Hello,
Which 3d printer you use, because the measurements of my bed are 220x220x240 and I cant print the wheel...
Thank you ;)

Quisiera imprimir la nueva versión reforzada y con las aperturas para la base de las palancas de cambio pero no se cual es.
Tanto en una como en la otra veo mas agujeros de sujeccion a la base del volante que en el de la versión de g25. Todos menos 2 parecen estar a las mismas disposiciones pero lo que no estoy seguro es de si son para diámetro de volante normal o el de g25/27.
En caso de no haber una versión reforzada compatible con los G25/27, podrías hacerla? O una galleta adaptadora como estas podría valer para montar la alguna de esas dos versiones en un G27?

author: joshie3095

description.text:
Sequential Shifter for simracing,highly inspired by http://www.derekspearedesigns.com/2015-dsd-pro-sequential.html

The part secuencial_taco.stl is printed on filaflex with 10% infill
Rest of parts with PLA and 30% infill

I´ve used 2 spare buttons fron Leo Bodnar http://www.leobodnar.com/shop/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=98_74&products_id=189

You need some M3 screws to attach secuencial_boton(print 2 of this) to secuencial_base part.

The part secuencial_taco is ready to screw if needed,but in my case is holded in place because tight fit.10% infill works well for me,you can change this value to your taste if you want a harder response.

The threaded rod and nylon nuts used for the axe are M8.You need some washers too to center the secuencial-puño inside the base.

In my case the shifter is attached to 45 mm T-slot profile with M8 T-screws and nuts.

The secuencial_puño part works well as is,but you can also print the secuencial_flex part and put the puño inside(i´ve used a hammer and a bit of patience:)

author: JFG7662

description.text:
This is a holder for the PROXXON micromot 50, to attach it to the Mendel90 x-carriage instead of the extruder. This way you can convert your Mendel90 into a CNC drilling and milling machine. I'm using this for drilling PCBs.

What I'm still missing is something to mount the PCB reliable. My provisorily test succeeded, though ;-)

Howto: Unlike 3d-printing I don't use the endstops. I manually drive the drill to a reference point using pronterface. Then I set the origin using "G92 X0 Y0 Z3", Z3, because Z0 is the max drill depth. The program in the video was hand crafted for testing, but this can also be generated using Eagle and the pcb-gcode plugin.

Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TKDHV7M1ohw

My test program:

G90 ; position absolute
G1 Z10 F250; start position
G1 X5.8 Y35.6 F2000 ; start position
G1 Z0 F100; first drill
G1 Z5 F250; retract
G1 X9.61 F2000 ; next pos
G1 Z0 F100; drill
G1 Z5 F250; retract
G1 X13.42 F2000 ; next pos
G1 Z0 F100; drill
G1 Z5 F250; retract
G1 X17.23 F2000 ; next pos
G1 Z0 F100; drill
G1 Z5 F250; retract
G1 X21.04 F2000 ; next pos
G1 Z0 F100; drill
G1 Z5 F250; retract
G1 Z30 F250; end pos

This test was done using an old garbage PCB, that's why the PCB looks so ugly ;-)

Tips:

  • Use G92 X0 Y0 Z0 for testing (without drilling). If it looks good change to Z3.
  • Also the travel lines in pronterface's 3D view is already very useful to verify the drill paths.

Have a look on my blog http://gergap.de/gcode-simulator.html for more information on etching PCBs using Eagle and pcb-gcode.

description.text:
This is a low-cost photo tent mainly used to take pictures of small objects.  This photo tent is easy to dismantle and to store.  
Look at the instructions for the BOM and information on how to build it.

You will need the following to build this tent:
  • 5 foam core board. I used 20 inches x 30 inches x 3/16 of an inch.
  • 4 front corner brackets.
  • 4 rear corner brackets.
  • 4 clip lamps.
  • 4 daylight light bulbs. I used Sylvania 100W DayLight bulbs.
  • 1 white card board
    • Mount the above as shown in the pictures. The foam core boards used for the side panels will need to be cut. Their length has to be the width of a board plus two times the board thickness. Make sure that the side panels are two times the board thickness longer. This way, you will not need to cut the back panel. Note that the board dimensions are slightly shorter than what the manufacturer says. Mines were 29" 15/16 x 19" 15/16. So, the length of my side panels are 20" 5/16.

comments.text: The pyramid base is a very very very bad idea :) No 3d printer can print this thing correctly. I love the Swiss cheese design, but please change the bottom side. Either make it flat or with some ridges. That way the printer can just bridge over the ridges. FYI and I am not being an ahole... the more single tiny points the printer needs to put down on the bed, the less it becomes feasible. title: Ducted Electronics Box Cover for Raise 3d N2 Series Printer

description.text:
This is a ducted cover for the Raise 3d N2 series' motion control box.
The cover has a mounting points to attach your control box fan to and is able to draw in fresh air from the cable access portal from the space under your printer.
The inlet port avoids stressing any cable connectors by offsetting the inlet to the left side of the box.

Reccormend printing 200-300um with 2-3 shells, 15% fill
My print was done in ABS, but PLA would also work.

Designed in Autodesk Inventor 2017.

Printer:

Raise 3D N2 Plus

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200um

Infill:

15%

Notes:

2-3 shells, ABS reccormended due to operating temperature considerations

I designed this after printing Raise3d's own ducted cover to discover it was interfering with all the cables and connectors and i couldnt close the cover without crushing the pcb usb socket.

So I designed this shortly after that dissapointing experience (do your QC Raise3d).
About 2 hours work in Autodesk Inventor 2017.

comments.text:
This is an excellent design.
I wasted quite a bit of time trying to print it with the parts lying down, when it is apparently best printed with the pieces standing vertically.
Unfortunately, when I did get the two parts printed well, they did not fit each other, and could not be assembled, so I remixed the parts to be a single printable piece: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2425721

author: techwit

description.text:
Bought a E3Pack from http://www.e3printable.no?

Want a spool to hang it on? Well here it is:)

Simple Spool that makes using E3Pack filament without a spool a breeze. It is made so that when it is assembled, you only needs a screwdriver to loosen the holders. The screws are long enough that you can actually lift and twist the holders without losing the nut. This makes even the smallest bundles workable.

This is made to work with all E3Packs delivered from http://www.e3printable.no

Supplied with it is adapters for M6,M8,Bearing 606 and Bearing 608. Also supplied is smaller holders in case you have a small spool holder.

The main hub is 30mm.

You will need:
3 M4x16 Screw/Bolt
3 M4 Small washer
3 M4 Nut
You Might need a drop of glue to make sure the adapters don't come loose. This will be individual to how accurate your printer is.

Printer:

K8200

No

Yes

Finally, salvation from the 6 million other awesome IPhone docks on Thingiverse has arrived! The Dock-O-Tron 5000 is an all purpose docking solution for the Iphone 5. Notably insignificant features include: -Side loading approach makes wire management easier. Simply plug your lightning cable and / or headphones into your phone and slide wires through the gap in the dock. Lightning is routed through the interference fit channel in the back and headphones are routed straight through the front.
-Passive amplification of Iphone's external speaker gives louder alerts.
-Passive amplification of your voice to the mic so you can talk while docked.
Printed well at .2 mm with 2 shells and 12.5% infill using KiSS on a Rostock type printer. Printer went down near the end so will upload pics of finished models after I recalibrate.

remixed_from.title: Case for DS1302 Rotation LED Electronic Clock Kit

title: Remixed DS1302 clock face to use for VFD rotating clock
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
OK, I have to admit: at this point of time, I do not have the knowledge yet to design my own 3D things. But it is amazing what other people design and how you can easilly re-use that creativity.

I printed the original clock face for my LED rotating DS1302 clock and I liked it a lot.

Recently I bought this really great clock kit: the VFD rotating clock. It looks great, but there is one problem: I have no suitable case. So I shrunk the Y dimensions and the X dimensions and doubled the Z dimensions and voila: I had a very nice box for my VFD clock!!

comments.text:
Yes, I was also directly in love when I saw the kit at https://www.kosbo.com/
Not very cheap, though, but there are some cheaper alternatives on Ebay.
